Williams started clicking, Alabama started winning.
article.headline: Crimson Tide now has won 22 in a row at home
article.linkText: Big run gets No. 5 Alabama going toward big win
article.story: TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- When Kenny Walker, Erwin Dudley and Mo Williams started clicking, Alabama (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today; No. 3 Associated Press) began living up to its high ranking. Dudley scored 18 points, Walker added a season-high 17 and Williams had 13 points and seven assists in the Crimson Tide's 89-61 victory over North Carolina-Greensboro on Tuesday night. ''We rarely have a bad shooting game at home,'' Williams said. ''I knew they were going to fall at home. ''When the big guys got it going, it just opened it up more for us.'' None of the three played more than 27 minutes for the Tide (5-0), which rode a 29-6 run into halftime and tied a 31-year-old school mark with its 22nd consecutive home victory. The Spartans (3-2) could cut only four points off the Tide's 32-point lead after Alabama's starters went to the bench for the final 10 minutes. Nine Alabama players scored at least five points. The Tide dominated the boards 46-32 and shot 48.6 percent after hitting 17 percent in the second half of a 54-48 victory over Ohio State on Friday night. ''They overpowered us,'' Spartans coach Fran McCaffery said. ''They were quicker to the ball, and they were the more aggressive team. If you're going to go on the road and play the No. 3 team, you have to get to the ball, and we didn't do that.'' James Maye led UNC-Greensboro with 13 points, all in the first half. Leading scorer Jay Joseph had nine points, eight below his season average. The Tide didn't start out looking particularly deserving of the high ranking with continued shooting troubles, then heated up for the big run over the final 8:50 in taking a 48-28 halftime lead. Walker and Dudley combined for 25 points before halftime as Alabama dominated the inside scoring 24-4, shot 51 percent and committed only one turnover. ''We moved the ball better tonight than we did against Ohio State,'' Alabama coach Mark Gottfried said. ''We've got a number of different guys that can make shots.'' The Tide started just 4-for-16 and trailed by six points early in the half. UNC-Greensboro was up 22-19 with nine minutes left. Then, reserve Reggie Rambo scored on a bank shot and a putback and Alabama followed shortly with 15 consecutive points. Walker had nine points in the run, setting up his own fastbreak dunk with a block on the other end. Alabama shot 48.6 percent and was 9-for-22 from 3-point range for its most lopsided victory and highest scoring game of the season. McCaffery said the Tide looked like a potential Final Four team. Gottfried is just hoping for freshmen Lucky Williams and Kennedy Winston to be declared eligible by the NCAA and give the team inside depth to match its bevy of guards. ''I think we're still missing a few things, but I like our defense,'' Gottfried said. ''I think we can substitute on the perimeter right now, and we're not missing a beat. Substituting on the inside, I'm not sure.''
